TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rural-Urban Differences in Job Satisfaction: Further Evidence
AU  - Martinson, Oscar B.
AU  - Wilkening, E. A.
Y1  - 1984/03/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255968
DO  - 10.5465/255968
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 199
EP  - 206
VL  - 27
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article focuses on a study which examined the impact of both size of place of socialization and place of current residence on rural-urban differences in job satisfaction. As far as the job level-extrinsic job satisfaction relationship is concerned, it appears that size of place of origin may moderate this relationship. It stresses the importance of specific measurement, especially regarding geographic areas of socialization. Experts say residential setting must be specified precisely to capture effects of the place of origin variables. The rural-urban differences in origin seem to explain the differences in intrinsic job satisfaction.
AB  - The article focuses on a study which examined the impact of both size of place of socialization and place of current residence on rural-urban differences in job satisfaction. As far as the job level-extrinsic job satisfaction relationship is concerned, it appears that size of place of origin may moderate this relationship. It stresses the importance of specific measurement, especially regarding geographic areas of socialization. Experts say residential setting must be specified precisely to capture effects of the place of origin variables. The rural-urban differences in origin seem to explain the differences in intrinsic job satisfaction.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255968
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255968
